We found that the intensity of surface plasmon resonance peak of CQD/Ag nanocomposites at 400nm decreases in the presence of methimazole. At the same time, a new peak appears around 500nm (Fig. 5
                        a) and the color of solution changes from yellow to red. TEM image of CQD/Ag nanocomposites in the presence of methimazole (Fig. 5b) shows that upon addition of this drug, the size of nanoparticles increases and their size distribution becomes broad (38±18nm). This is probably due to the binding of methimazole to Ag atoms on the surface of NPs, via Ag-S bond [5], which may destabilize them and cause aggregation of some small NPs to form larger nanocomposites. On the basis of these results, a novel colorimetric method can be developed for the determination of methimazole (Scheme 1
                        ).

Under the optimum conditions mentioned above, the analytical figures of merit for determination of methimazole were obtained. The calibration curve was linear in the concentration range of 2.0 − 40μgL−1 with a detection limit (3s) of 1.0μgL−1 (Fig. 7
                        ). The regression equation was ΔA=0.018C − 0.016, R2
                        =0.9984, where ΔA=A0-A is the difference between the absorbance in the absence of methimazole (A0) and in its presence (A), and C is concentration of methimazole (μgL−1). The relative standard deviation (RSD%) was 2.1% for five replicate determinations of 20μgL−1 methimazole. The results indicate that this colorimetric method has a good linearity, high sensitivity and suitable precision for determination of methimazole. Our method provides a better detection limit than most other reported analytical methods for methimazole (Table S1, ESM).
